{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17647770","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17647770"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T20:47:30+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T20:47:30+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18262"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"18262","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/18262"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0,0.07,0.59,0.24,0.1]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10976"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"79300"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"10976","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/10976"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18262"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"64622"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4931"},{"type":"tags","id":"4941"},{"type":"tags","id":"10232"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"25500"},{"type":"contributions","id":"25502"},{"type":"contributions","id":"27140"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"79300","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/79300"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003E The semimembranosus, semitendinosus and biceps femoris are three muscles in the lower limb.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following movements are these muscles responsible for?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Hip extension, knee extension","Hip extension only","Hip extension, knee flexion","Hip flexion, knee extension","Hip flexion, knee flexion"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe semimembranosus, semitendinosus, and biceps femoris are muscles located in the posterior compartment of the thigh. They are collectively known as the hamstring muscles.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe semimembranosus, semitendinosus, and biceps femoris are responsible for \u003Cstrong\u003Ehip extension and knee flexion\u003C/strong\u003E. These muscles are part of the hamstring group, which is located at the back of the thigh. They play a key role in movements such as walking, running, and jumping by extending the hip and flexing the knee.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHip extension, knee extension\u003C/strong\u003E - The hamstrings do not extend the knee; they flex it\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHip flexion, knee extension\u003C/strong\u003E - The hamstrings extend the hip and flex the knee, not the other way around\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHip flexion, knee flexion\u003C/strong\u003E - The hamstrings extend the hip, not flex it\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHip extension only\u003C/strong\u003E - While the hamstrings do extend the hip, they also flex the knee\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["The semimembranosus, semitendinosus, and biceps femoris are part of the hamstring muscle group.","These muscles are responsible for hip extension and knee flexion.","The hamstring muscles play a crucial role in movements such as walking, running, and jumping."],"references":["Sud, A., \u0026 Ranjan, R. (2018). Textbook of Orthopaedics, -E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences","Singh, V. (2018). Textbook of Anatomy Abdomen and Lower Limb; Volume II (Vol. 2). Elsevier Health Sciences","Cantrell AJ, Imonugo O, Varacallo M. Anatomy, Bony Pelvis and Lower Limb: Leg Bones. [Updated 2023 Aug 14]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan-. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK537024/","Raftery A. General Anatomy and Musculoskeletal System. Ann R Coll Surg Engl. 2006 Jul;88(4):425. doi: 10.1308/003588406X114802d. PMCID: PMC1964629","Chaudhry SR, Nahian A, Chaudhry K. Anatomy, Abdomen and Pelvis, Pelvis. [Updated 2023 Jul 25]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan-. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK482258/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"64622"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18262"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"64622","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/64622"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-14T08:50:37+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-14T08:51:24+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10976"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"79300"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identify